      <h1>XRPL Nodes Guide</h1>
      <p class="post-lead">Understanding XRP Ledger node types, how to connect to them, and when it makes sense to run your own versus using a managed provider like XRPL Stream.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="post-body">
      <h2>Node types</h2>
      <p>The XRP Ledger network consists of several types of nodes, each serving a different purpose:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Validator nodes:</strong> Participate in the consensus process. They propose and vote on which transactions to include in each ledger. The XRPL uses a unique consensus protocol (not proof-of-work or proof-of-stake) where trusted validators agree on transaction ordering. There are roughly 150+ validators on the network, with about 35 on Ripple's recommended Unique Node List (UNL).</li>
        <li><strong>Stock nodes:</strong> Track the current state of the ledger and serve API requests. They do not participate in consensus but maintain a connection to the network and process incoming transactions. Most developers interact with stock nodes.</li>
        <li><strong>Full history nodes:</strong> Stock nodes that store the complete ledger history from genesis (ledger 32,570 in January 2013). These require significant storage -- currently around 39 TB and growing. Most stock nodes only keep recent history (days or weeks).</li>
        <li><strong>Clio nodes:</strong> Specialized read-only nodes optimized for API serving. Clio stores data in Cassandra/ScyllaDB and is designed for high-throughput query workloads. Ripple's public servers (s1.ripple.com, s2.ripple.com) run Clio.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Hardware requirements</h2>
      <p>Running your own XRPL node requires dedicated hardware:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stock node (recent history):</strong> 8 CPU cores, 32 GB RAM, 500 GB SSD. Stores approximately 2-4 weeks of ledger history.</li>
        <li><strong>Full history node:</strong> 8+ CPU cores, 64+ GB RAM, 39+ TB NVMe storage. The storage requirement grows by roughly 1-2 TB per month.</li>
        <li><strong>Validator:</strong> Same as stock node, plus reliable uptime and network connectivity. Validators should be professionally hosted with redundant infrastructure.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The storage requirement for full history is the biggest barrier. At 39 TB, NVMe storage alone costs $3,000-5,000+ depending on hosting provider. This is why most developers use managed RPC providers instead of running their own full history node.</p>

      <h2>Public RPC endpoints</h2>
      <p>Several organizations provide free public access to XRPL nodes:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>s1.ripple.com / s2.ripple.com:</strong> Ripple's public Clio servers. Full history, but rate limited. Good for development, not suitable for production workloads.</li>
        <li><strong>xrplcluster.com:</strong> Community-run rippled cluster. Full history, relatively generous rate limits.</li>
        <li><strong>xrpl.link:</strong> Another community rippled endpoint. Full history.</li>
        <li><strong>XRPL Stream (s1.xrpl.stream):</strong> Managed 21-node edge network. Full history, dedicated endpoints, guaranteed rate limits, global distribution.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Connecting via WebSocket</h2>
      <p>The primary way to interact with XRPL nodes is through WebSocket connections. This allows bidirectional communication -- you can send requests and also subscribe to real-time events like ledger closes and transaction notifications. Most XRPL client libraries (xrpl.js, xrpl-py, xrpl4j) use WebSocket under the hood.</p>

      <h2>JSON-RPC over HTTP</h2>
      <p>Nodes also accept JSON-RPC requests over HTTP POST. This is simpler for one-off queries -- you send a request and get a response. No persistent connection needed. XRPL Stream supports both WebSocket and JSON-RPC on the same endpoint.</p>

      <h2>Mainnet, testnet, and devnet</h2>
      <p>The XRPL has three networks:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mainnet:</strong> The production network where real XRP transactions happen.</li>
        <li><strong>Testnet:</strong> A parallel network for testing. Free test XRP is available from faucets. Testnet mirrors mainnet features and is reset periodically.</li>
        <li><strong>Devnet:</strong> An experimental network where new amendments and features are tested before reaching testnet or mainnet.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why use a managed provider</h2>
      <p>Running your own XRPL node is viable for validators and organizations that need complete control. But for API access, a managed provider like XRPL Stream offers significant advantages:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No infrastructure to maintain:</strong> No servers, no storage, no upgrades</li>
        <li><strong>Full history included:</strong> Every transaction since 2013, no 39 TB storage bill</li>
        <li><strong>Global distribution:</strong> 21 nodes across 9 regions, queries served from nearest node</li>
        <li><strong>Guaranteed uptime:</strong> Redundant infrastructure with automatic failover</li>
        <li><strong>Free tier available:</strong> Start building immediately, scale when needed</li>
      </ul>

